'''Charles Carter Schnetzler''' (June 3, 1930&nbsp;– December 15, 2009) was a [[planetary scientist]] at [[NASA]]'s [[Goddard Space Flight Center]]. Schnetzler is best known for analyzing [[moon rock]]s brought back by the [[Apollo program]] and for studying the Earth's environment using the [[Landsat]] and the [[Earth Observing System]]. Schnetzler was born in [[Whiting, Indiana]] and grew up in [[Neodesha, Kansas]]. <ref name="Schudel">{{cite news|last=Schudel|first=Matt|date=January 14, 2010|title=Charles Schnetzler dies; was authority on planetary sciences|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/13/AR2010011304543.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> On November 4, 2009, Schnetzler was seriously injured after being hit by a car while walking near his home on Little Patuxent Parkway in [[Columbia, Maryland]].<ref name="Rita">{{cite news|last=Rita|first=Mike Santa|date=November 5, 2009|title=Columbia man, 79, hit by car, in critical condition|url=http://www.explorehoward.com/news/66896/columbia-man-79-hit-car-critical-condition/|newspaper=Columbia Flyer}}</ref> He later died in his home on December 15, 2009.<ref name="Schudel"/>

